When a chemically-propelled rocket is fired from Earth, we need a large 
amount of fuel to get any payload on orbit. In addition, we need even more 
fuel to lift the fuel needed to lift the payload, and even more fuel to 
lift that fuel. 
The majority of any orbit-height rocket's weight has to be fuel in order to 
generate enough lift force to get it to the orbit, and more than 96%(!!!) 
of the weight of the fully loaded space shuttle has to be just the fuel.

On Earth, gravity is low enough to allow reaching the escape velocity using 
just conventional fuel. What is quite interesting, if we lived on only a 
little larger planet, we would need a lot more energy-dense fuel to be able 
to lift any payload out of the gravitational field of that planet. Even if 
we used mathematically-optimal rockets with multiple to maximize the 
rocket's efficiency, if the gravity would be high enough, it would be 
physically impossible to escape the planet's gravity from the ground using 
chemical fuels of any kind, even the hydrogen-oxygen mix we use (one of the 
most energy-dense chemical fuels in existence).

I would really like to know how large the gravity of a planet would need to

comments.text:
Right- what we are looking for is the minimum sized planet that cannot be 
escaped using a rocket made with all the fuel in the planet's crust. To 
make things easier I will assume that all the fuel used will be kerosene, 
which is the limiting factor when it comes to rarity, rather than the 
metals used to create the exterior. I will also have to assume the new 
planet has the same crust composition and the same density.

I'm going to have to do this by trial and error. Let's start with a radius 
of 2x the Earth's.
Vp = volume of new planet, Mp = mass of new planet, Me = mass of Earth, r = 
radius of new planet, Sp = surface (crust) mass of new planet, Se = surface 
mass of Earth, E = Earth

1. Work out the mass of the planet. Vp = 4/3 * pi * r^3. Strip away 
constants: Vp is proportional to Mp is proportional to r^3. r = 2xE, so r^3 
= 8xE. Mp = Me * 8 = 4.776*10^25

2. Find orbital velocity at 200km above surface: V = root(G*Mp/r) = 12.871 
km/s
(rocket will need about 25% more than this, so we'll call the rocket dV 
15.87 km/s)

3. Find the mass of the rocket. Assume a crew capsule is 500kg, and every 
1km/s of dV requires the rocket mass to increase by 1.4x. Thus, m = 500 * 
1.4^15.87 = 104237 kg.

4. Find the mass of fuel required, 90% of rocket mass: 93813 kg = 
9.38*10^4kg

5. Find total fuel in new planet's crust, same densities as Earth: Kerosene 
on Earth: 1.585*10^10kg * 4 ~= 6*10^10kg.

We can see in this example that the fuel required to leave would require 
9.38*10*4kg of kerosene, not a patch on the 6*10^10kg in the crust of the 
planet. We clearly need to go a lot bigger.

A planet with 10x the radius of Earth would need 6.379x10^15kg of fuel, 
which is more than the 1.585*10^12kg in the crust. This would be 
inescapable, so we need to go lower.

Through a lot of trial and error, I eventually found that the maximum-sized 
earth-like planet escapable using conventional rockets is around 6x larger 
than Earth itself. This planet is 200 times the mass of Earth and so would 
hold onto hydrogen and helium in it's formation, bringing it's mass up even 
higher until it ended up something like a brown dwarf. The planet described 
would, therefore, never exist.

However, this assumes that we can get all the kerosene on the entire planet 
and put it in one giant rocket, which is ridiculous in more ways than one. 
So, practically, the maximum-sized planet we could escape to orbit from 
would be far smaller, perhaps only 2 or 3 times as large.

Oh, and I know I simplified a lot. There's a reason for that. Don't make me 
do it all again.

Light is a particle that behaves like a wave. We call it a photon. 
Different objects affect these particles differently. For example, light 
can not go through a brick wall. This is because the electrons in the atoms 
that make up the wall absorb the photons, and then release the energy 
randomly whenever they want. When an object is black, it is absorbing 100% 
of the photons that come into contact with it. We can still see black metal 
because the electrons in a piece of metal don't stay bound to one atom, but 
move around from atom to atom. This causes the metallic shine and it only 
requires a sheet a few atoms thick to get this result. The blackest thing 
would probably be a black hole. I am not going to pretend I fully 
understand a black hole as currently we only have quantum mechanics and 
thermodynamics that allow us to study them, but what appears to happen is 
the light around a black hole is "bent" i.e., knocked off course, therefore 
making the object behind the black hole look deformed. If the photons get 
close enough to the black hole (to the area we call the event horizon) the 
light gets sucked in and after this we do not know what happens. Hope this 
helped answer your question!

comments.text:
Michael's explanation of quantum mechanics is not understandable because he 
is WRONG.  He misrepresents what Bell's theorem actually claims to do.  
Speak to any expert on the theorem and they will tell you that it DOES NOT 
PROVE THAT THE UNIVERSE IS RANDOM.  All the theorem claims is that if you 
assume that entangled particles can "talk" to one another no faster than 
the speed of light and that quantum entanglements take place within a 
single universe, it is mathematically impossible to reproduce the 
correlations between the spins of entangled particles recorded in 
real-world experiments.  This means that quantum theories that lack 
randomness can agree with the theorem so long as they permit 
faster-than-light interactions by some means and/or assume that quantum 
events occur over several parallel universes. 

De Broglie-Bohm theory (a.k.a. pilot-wave theory because wave-shaped forces 
"pilot" particles around to, for example, generate the interference pattern 
from the double-slit experiment) is a nonrandom version of quantum 
mechanics which does not contradict Bell's theorem because it permits 
faster-than-light interactions (John Bell himself was an advocate of de 
Broglie-Bohm).  The many-worlds interpretation of quantum mechanics 
likewise contains no random element and yet can coexist with Bell's theorem 
because it posits the existence of parallel universes to explain 
entanglement as well as other kinds of quantum phenomena.

More controversially, over the past few years, a physicist named Joy 
Christian, a former student of the world-famous expert in Bell's theorem 
Abner Shimony, has been claiming to have discovered that Bell's theorem is 
actually only true if you presume that the space through which entangled 
particles move is a certain shape.  Christian wrote an alternate version of 
Bell's theorem using a different shape called a 3-sphere, and using this 
new mathematical model, several computer simulations have been written by a 
number of different people which appear to be able to reproduce real-world 
spin correlations without the use of parallel universes, faster-than-light 
interactions, or randomness.  Christian has proposed an experiment 
involving exploding balls that will be able to definitively demonstrate 
whether or not he's right.

BOTTOM LINE—THERE IS NO PROOF THAT QUANTUM PHYSICS IS RANDOM, AND IF

comments.text:
+avdagamer Well technically, if ours eyes even viewed the world in frames, 
then that slow motion guy comment would be totally false. That's not how 
slow motion works. 

If our eyes saw in frames per second (say 60 fps for the sake of 
discussion), then our eyes would be 'recording' and 'playing back' in the 
exact same frame rate, causing the world to go at normal speed. However, if 
our eyes were defective and saw at a higher frame rate (say 120 fps), then 
they would still be recording and playing back at the same frame rate 
causing life to go at normal speed still.

The way slow motion works is that the recording fps is higher than the 
playback fps. For example, if I recorded a 10 second video at 120 fps, 
there would be 120 frames recorded every second evening out to 1200 frames. 
Played back in real time (120 fps because that's the recording speed) the 
screen would be displaying 120 frames every time a second passed (duh). If, 
however, we played it back at 60 frames per second, there would still be 
the same amount of frames. However, since the frames are being displayed 
slower, the overall time increases. Instead of 120 frames per second, there 
would be 60 frames per second (duh), doubling the total time to 20 seconds. 
This creates an effect that we perceive as slow motion. 

Reversely, if you play back that 120 fps clip and 240 fps, the total time 
would be halved causing 'fast motion.'

TL;DR fps is irrelevant when it comes to slow motion/real time. It all 
comes down to recording and playback speed.

comments.text:
It's usually through an algorithm that is predictable and deterministic, 
but is fed by a practically random value for its initial condition, usually 
the current date and time specified in milliseconds. The results of the 
generator, if graphed, may seem random at first, but will eventually start 
to have a discernible pattern if you wait long enough. How long it takes 
for this pattern to appear depends on the initial conditions, the 
complexity of the algorithm, and the range of results specified. In any 
case, numbers generated in this fashion aren't really random, but 
*pseudorandom*.

You are confusing the "uncertainty principle" with the "observer effect". 
The uncertainty principle states that there are complementary variables, 
that by knowing one, you can't know the other.

The "observer effect" means that by measuring we are interfering with the 
particle, and physicists are working on trying to get around this by doing 
"weak measurements" which very simply means doing measurements that affect 
the system very little, but also tell you very little. By combining many 
such measurements, you can get useful answers.

The randomness doesn't have anything to do with measurements. Particles are 
just random :)

Lets say you have a dice.  Each value is equally likely to land...so its 
truly random, assuming its a fair dice.  But if you had somethign where a 
particular result is more likely than another (like in quantum wave 
function) its no longer random because you can make meaningful predictions 
about the next value.

Take a deck of cards.  Which card you pull off the top of the deck is 
random, each card is equally likely or each value is equally likely. 
 However, once you remove one Ace, pulling an Ace is less likely than any 
other card and it is no longer truly random as you can predict with a 
particular accuracy the next card being NOT  an Ace.  The order is still 
random, but by knowing that one ace can no longer be drawn you have 
information that can be used to predict the next card....if you draw enough 
cards, your predictions can become ever more accurate and eventually you 
will know with certainty what the next card is (on the last card).  Since 
the probabilities of each value is not equal (because of the information 
you gain) its no longer "truly random".   You cannot have any information 
that makes predictions easier in a system that is truly random.

comments.text:
The claims Michael makes about quantum mechanics in this video are 
factually untrue, plain and simple: Bell’s theorem does not disprove 
determinism; it only professes to demonstrate that quantum entanglement can 
never be fully explained in terms of local hidden variables—that is, hidden 
properties which cannot transmit information faster than light.  For 
example, de Broglie-Bohm theory is completely deterministic but nonetheless 
still in complete agreement with Bell’s theorem.  In fact, John Bell 
himself was one of de Broglie-Bohm theory’s most ardent proponents!  It’s 
ironic that Michael is attempting to prove indeterminacy in quantum physics 
using the work of a man who was actually one of a handful of contrarians in 
the physics community fighting against the dogma of quantum randomness.

The misconception often espoused by science popularizers that quantum 
physics is fundamentally random really stems from a much older proof 
written by John von Neumann which claimed to rule out ALL hidden-variable 
explanations that might conceivably eliminate indeterminacy from quantum 
theory.  This theorem was regarded as sacrosanct for decades.  However, 
John von Neumann’s proof has since been discredited.  Can you guess who 
debunked him?  None other than John Bell.

comments.text:
Having taken a fair amount of philosophy, I'll offer some input. I can 
sometimes be a bit pedantic, so let me know if anything needs further 
explanation.

You have interesting ideas, but I think you stretch a few of your analogies 
too far and give too much importance to perspective. The issues you raise 
regarding perspective are actually epistemological in nature, whereas you 
make them out to have some actual impact on the way the world actually is. 
It's not an issue for objective reality if everyone in the world was 
schizophrenic, it's an issue for the schizophrenics in that their mental 
representations of reality do not correspond to the way things actually 
are. Everyone does not have "their own" reality, everyone has their own 
mental representations that (we would like to) correspond to reality, 
whatever the actual state of things turns out to be. (And nobody's 
perception of reality has to correctly represent reality; this would 
probably be the case in a world full of schizophrenics.) Presumably, 
objective reality is a determining factor in our perspective, not the other 
way around.

Reality itself is not simply a consensus agreement, the labels we apply to 
things and the attached semantics are. Since our beliefs and knowledge are 
heavily based on the semantics of these labels, it is easy to think that 
what we know, and therefore reality itself, is just consensus, but a 
careful analysis reveals that this is not the case. 

A more analytical look at a few more of your analogies reveal that they are 
also problematic. For example, in the dark room analogy you use the word 
"dark" in several different ways. One is to describe the absence of 
wavelengths on the visible spectrum, in which case the room is dark. 
Another is to describe the absence of ANY wavelengths in the room, in which 
case the room is not "dark" (as there are infrared waves in the room). Call 
these different uses of the word "Dark1" and "Dark2", respectively. Thus, 
the room is Dark1, but not Dark2. (Fun fact: We do not "filter out" 
wavelengths outside of the visible spectrum, we simply do not have the 
correct receptors for them, while the camera does.) Notice that this 
explanation of the room shows one completely consistent view of reality, 
with no dependance on perspective or anyone observing the electromagnetic 
radiation in the first place. We see once again that objective reality 
influences perspective, not the other way around. Perspective is not 
reality, perspective represents reality.
 
I partially agree with you on the real/fake issue, in that I think they're 
meaningless labels in any sort of technical sense. If Y is a fake X, it 
seems enough to say that Y is not a member of the set of X things, or that 
Y is Z and Z is not a member of the set of X things, etc. If Y is a real X, 
then Y is a member of X. I do not, however, think that real and fake are 
the same thing, I simply think that there is no interesting way to apply 
those labels at a technical level that is not covered by what I've already 
said. For instance, Y cannot simultaneously be a member of X and not a 
member of X. I'd bet you could not come up with an example of this being 
the case without committing an equivocation fallacy. (For example, saying 
that a room is both dark and not dark when what you really mean is that the 
room is Dark1, but not Dark2. The fallacy occurs when you imply that Dark1 
= Dark2.)

Your argument of God being everything and the ant's perspective just being 
the same as a human's perspective just seems convoluted to me. Even if ants 
and humans are made of the same stuff, it does not follow that everything 
about them is the same (fallacy of composition/modo hoc fallacy). It's also 
relevant that humans consist of much more "stuff", and have much more 
complicated functionality in terms of neuronal connections. In any case, it 
doesn't seem like anything you say in that paragraph really follows.

One last note, I would also have to disagree that the universe is 
inherently binary. Quantum computers, for example, do not operate on 
binary. Quantum mechanics is described in terms of probabilities, not 
binary. I would venture to say that the universe (or any possible universe, 
for that matter) is logically consistent, but I doubt one can relevantly 
derive much from that fact alone. In any case, if your argument is based on 
the premise that the universe is inherently binary, I would have to say 
that your argument is unsound.

TL;DR: One's perception of reality =/= reality itself.

Wow thanks! I like to see people asking questions and being open to discuss 
physics.

Finding the half life a similar process for any isotope, first an 
experimenter needs to think of a way to detect decays, probably by 
detecting some decay product (for example, Bi-209 emits an alpha particle 
according to google).

Then you count the number of decays you measure every second or minute or 
whatever. You would then plot this data on a graph (time elapsed vs. 
decays/second) and fit it to an exponential decay function which will 
contain the half-life. It's a simple process but kind of hard to explain in 
a youtube comment.

What JandCan0 said is how we can find half-life even though the timing of 
decay is random.

As for sources, that's a bit tough since physics sources tend to be tough 
to take in in a single session or even over a couple of weeks, I'm a fourth 
year physics student so I've had a bit of time to digest this stuff. 
Radioactive decay w/o quantum mechanics is a high school physics topic, so 
you can look up videos or read the wiki page for exponential decay, since 
that's pretty much all there is to it on that level. For the quantum stuff 
discussed in this video and comments.. (randomness, probabilities) for a 
quick conceptual understanding I would suggest going to the wikipedia 
"intro to quantum mechanics" page, skip ahead to the "Copenhagen 
interpretation", read through the principles there and look up terms and 
ideas whenever you see one you don't understand. I think that's a good 
starting point. Be careful of quantum mechanics videos on youtube, stick to 
NOVA/reputable scientific sources and legit lectures. I say this because a 
lot of crazy people try to use QM to push their pseudoscience bullshit and

is mostly a complete vacuum, which means there are very few forces and 
other physical variables to account for when calculating the movement of 
celestial bodies. This makes predicting the movement of objects through 
space very easy to calculate mathematically. On Earth, the air itself is 
filled with molecular particles that constantly bump into each other (most 
of these molecules are nitrogen, some are oxygen, and the rest is composed 
of carbon dioxide, methane, helium, etc). On a micro scale, these may seem 
trivial, random, and of little interest, but on a grander scale, it's this 
interaction between molecules in the air that creates gusts of wind and 
weather. But even with our current powerful technologies, it is impossible 
to know exactly how fast and in which direction every molecule in the air 
is moving - they are simply too quick, too small, and too numerous to keep 
track. This is precisely why predicting tomorrow's forecast is more 
difficult than predicting a solar Eclipse thousands of years into the 
future.

You are kind of wrong! Constructive interference means that similar noises 
do "stack," so to speak. However, constructive interference is on a scale 
that usually pales in comparison to the fall-off of "loudness" over a 
distance, meaning that what would actually happen if everyone yelled at 
once would really just be a measurement of how tightly packed people are 
when they yelled (and, secondarily, how much overlap there is in their 
vocal frequencies). This question has been studied in depth by a lot of 
people, but the actual answer would be incredibly difficult to measure 
quantitatively. Unless we move people, the noise would be loudest in the 
areas of highest population density. EXCEPT acoustic dampeners in the 
surrounding environment like, you know, *buildings* would mitigate the 
effect and it's no coincidence that these are most prolific where 
population density is highest, so probably very little would happen.

The effect would be much more noticeable if you moved everybody together 
into one place, but it would still be very difficult to measure and would 
basically depend, as before, on how tightly you can cram people together 
and how closely you can get them to harmonize their voices. At the core of 
the crowd, the noise would be deafening; at the edges, barely louder than 
normal. Timing would also be important! Sound doesn't move instantaneously 
and constructive interference is based on waveform crests momentarily 
overlapping, so you wouldn't want everyone to yell all at once if we're 
trying to maximize loudness: if the people at the outside yelled first and 
the people inside followed suit in a kind of "vocal wave" then we could get 
the effect to propagate inward and be even louder. The speed of sound is 
very fast compared to how fast people can yell, however, so this would 
require absurdly precise coordination.

In any case, the vibrations wouldn't cause an earthquake or anything. They 
might shatter glass or shake the surrounding area, but as with the age-old 
"breaking a wineglass by singing" trick this isn't actually an indicator of 
loudness, just of harmonic oscillation. Certainly, most people involved 
would have serious hearing damage, but this happens all the time: many 
people experience hearing loss from being in large crowds at concert 
festivals and so forth.
